# MathBot – Cline Rules
# This file is automatically read by Cline before every task.

## Context loading (always do this first)
- Read MEMORY.md first — understand what was done last session and what to continue
- Read CLAUDE.md before starting any task
- Read docs/PROJECT_STATUS.md to understand what's done and what's next
- Read the relevant docs/ file before working on a specific area:
  - Working on database/models → read docs/DATABASE.md
  - Working on API routes → read docs/API_SPEC.md
  - Working on chatbot/RAG → read docs/AI_CHATBOT.md
  - Working on deployment → read docs/DEPLOYMENT.md
  - Working on tests → read docs/TESTING.md
  - Adding questions/knowledge → read docs/SEEDING.md

## Auto-sync rules (do these automatically — never skip)

### When modifying prisma/schema.prisma
- Update docs/DATABASE.md — add/edit the model, update the relationships diagram
- Update docs/PROJECT_STATUS.md — mark the related task as ✅
- Run `npx prisma migrate dev --name describe_the_change`
- Run `npx prisma generate`

### When adding or modifying an API route
- Update docs/API_SPEC.md — add/edit the endpoint, request, response format
- If a new error code is needed, add it to docs/ERROR_CODES.md AND src/lib/errors.ts
- Update docs/PROJECT_STATUS.md — mark the related task as ✅

### When adding a new feature or module
- Update docs/ARCHITECTURE.md — add the module description and extension points
- Update docs/FEATURE_FLAGS.md — add a flag for the new feature
- Update src/lib/flags.ts — add the flag to the flags object
- Update docs/PROJECT_STATUS.md — add the new tasks with ⬜ status
- If an architectural decision was made, create a new file in docs/decisions/

### When modifying the RAG pipeline or AI behavior
- Update docs/AI_CHATBOT.md — reflect the changes in pipeline, prompts, or config
- Update docs/PROJECT_STATUS.md — mark the related task as ✅

### When adding a new feature flag
- Add to docs/FEATURE_FLAGS.md (the table + description)
- Add to src/lib/flags.ts (the flags object)
- Add to .env.example (with a comment)

### When adding a new error code
- Add to docs/ERROR_CODES.md (the registry table)
- Add to src/lib/errors.ts (the ErrorCode object)
- Never rename or remove existing codes — mark as [DEPRECATED] instead

### When completing any task
- Update docs/PROJECT_STATUS.md — change ⬜ to ✅
- Add a row to the Change log table with today's date and what changed
- Update MEMORY.md — move completed items out of "What is NOT done yet", update "Last working on"

### At the end of every session (when user says done / stop / goodbye / exit)
- Update MEMORY.md "Current session" with everything completed
- Update "What is NOT done yet" so next session resumes instantly
- Add a summary row to "Session history" table

### When installing a new package
- Update CLAUDE.md tech stack table if it's a major dependency
- Add any required environment variables to .env.example with a comment

## Before writing any code
- Check docs/PROJECT_RULES.md — follow every rule without exception
- Check docs/FEATURE_FLAGS.md — if the feature has a flag, gate it properly
- Check docs/ERROR_CODES.md — use existing codes, never invent new error strings

## Code rules (summary — full rules in docs/PROJECT_RULES.md)
- Always use TypeScript — never create .js files
- All API routes must be under src/app/api/v1/
- Always validate API input with Zod
- Always use Prisma Client — no raw SQL except pgvector search
- Always check session/auth at the top of every API route handler
- Always use AppError from src/lib/errors.ts for error handling
- Always render math with KaTeX — never Unicode math characters
- Never hardcode secrets — use process.env only
- Never use `any` TypeScript type
- Never hard-delete records that affect historical data — use isActive: false

## Project context
- Stack: Next.js 14 App Router, TypeScript, Prisma, PostgreSQL, pgvector, OpenAI, KaTeX, Tailwind, Zod
- Subject: Grade 12 Math exam prep chatbot (Vietnamese high school)
- Topics: FUNCTION_ANALYSIS, DERIVATIVES, INTEGRALS, EXPONENTIAL_LOGARITHM, LIMITS_AND_CONTINUITY, SOLID_GEOMETRY, VOLUMES, COMBINATORICS_PROBABILITY, ANALYTIC_GEOMETRY, SEQUENCES, COMPLEX_NUMBERS
